	</form></div><span class="pb doctop" title="page number in print edition" id="ADMS-06-16-02-pb-0570">570<a style="padding-left: 5px" onclick="window.open('/img-document-get.xqy?image=ADMS/Pages/ADMS-06-16/ADMS-06-16-02-pb-0570.jpg', 'pageImage', 'scrollbars=1,resizable=1'); return false" onkeypress="this.onclick();" tabindex="0" title="Click to view image of page from print edition"><img src="/img-ML/page-icon.gif" width="18" height="20" style="vertical-align:middle;" alt="page icon"/></a></span><div class="doc">
      
      <h1>From C. W. F. Dumas</h1>
      <div class="docbody">
        <div class="opener">
          <table class="salutationBlock">
        <tr>
		<td class="salutationLeft">Monsieur,</td>
		<td class="salutationRight">Lahaie 18 Mars 1785</td>
	      </tr>
      </table>
        </div>
        <p style="text-indent: 1.5em; text-align: left;">Depuis quelques jours mon Epouse, un peu mieux, me laisseroit sans peine pour elle, si lextrme foiblesse qui lui reste, ne minquiettoit encore.</p>
        <p style="text-indent: 1.5em; text-align: left;">Les projets sur la Baviere drangs, paroissent avoir fait prendre le parti de vouloir sen ddomager aux dpens de la Rep., qui ne peut se rsoudre  souscrire aux nouvelles propositions quon lui fait; &amp; par consquent je crains que nous nayions enfin la guerre.<a class="ptr" href="#ADMS-06-16-02-0334-fn-0001" id="ADMS-06-16-02-0334-fn-0001-ptr">1</a></p>
        <p style="text-indent: 1.5em; text-align: left;">Come jignore la rsidence actuelle du Congrs, je la laisse en blanc sur ladresse de lune des deux incluses, priant V. E. de vouloir bien y suppler.<a class="ptr" href="#ADMS-06-16-02-0334-fn-0002" id="ADMS-06-16-02-0334-fn-0002-ptr">2</a></p>
        <p style="text-indent: 1.5em; text-align: left;">Mad<span class="hi-super" style="font-size: 80%; line-height: 0.8; vertical-align: super;">e.</span> Van Berckel, dont la fille aine va partir pour aller auprs de Mr. son pere, mayant demand si elle ne risquoit rien des Barbaresques, dans un Vaisseau Amricain prt  partir dAmsterdam, en prenant par le Nord. Mon opinion, que je lui ai fait connotre, est, quil ny a rien  craindre par cette voie, &amp; dans cette saison. Si je me trompois, un prompt avertissement de la part de V. E. me mettroit  mme de me retracter, &amp; de prserver Mad<span class="hi-super" style="font-size: 80%; line-height: 0.8; vertical-align: super;">le.</span> Van Berckel du malheur dtre prise. Bien nos respects  Mesdames Adams, De Votre Excellence le trs humble &amp; trs obeissant Serviteur</p>
        <div class="closer">
          <p class="signed">Cwf Dumas</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="translation">
        <h2>TRANSLATION</h2>
        <div class="opener">
          <table class="salutationBlock">
        <tr>
		<td class="salutationLeft">Sir</td>
		<td class="salutationRight">The Hague, 18 March 1785</td>
	      </tr>
      </table>
        </div>
        <p style="text-indent: 1.5em; text-align: left;">For several days my spouse has been a bit better, which would have alleviated my concern for her if the extreme weakness that persists did not keep me worrying still.</p>
        <p style="text-indent: 1.5em; text-align: left;">The schemes for Bavaria being upset seems to have occasioned a determination to try to make up for it at the expense of the republic, which cannot bring itself to sign the new proposals that are made to it, and consequently I fear that we will in the end have a war.<a class="ptr" href="#ADMS-06-16-02-0334-fn-0001" id="ADMS-06-16-02-0334-fn-0001-ptr">1</a></p>
        <span class="pb center" title="page number in print edition" id="ADMS-06-16-02-pb-0571">[571<a style="padding-left: 0px" onclick="window.open('/img-document-get.xqy?image=ADMS/Pages/ADMS-06-16/ADMS-06-16-02-pb-0571.jpg', 'pageImage', 'scrollbars=1,resizable=1'); return false" onkeypress="this.onclick();" tabindex="0" title="Click to view image of page from print edition"><img src="/img-ML/page-icon.gif" width="18" height="20" style="vertical-align:middle;" alt="page icon"/></a>]</span>
        <p style="text-indent: 1.5em; text-align: left;">As I do not know where Congress currently resides, I am leaving blank the address on one of the two enclosures, asking your excellency to be so kind as to supply it.<a class="ptr" href="#ADMS-06-16-02-0334-fn-0002" id="ADMS-06-16-02-0334-fn-0002-ptr">2</a></p>
        <p style="text-indent: 1.5em; text-align: left;">Mrs. Van Berckel, whose elder daughter is leaving to go to her father, asked me if she risked anything from the Barbaries in an American vessel, one of which is ready to depart from Amsterdam, taking the northern route. My opinion, which I let her know, is that there is nothing to fear along that route in this season. If I am mistaken, a prompt warning from your excellency would enable me to recant and to save Miss Van Berckel from the misfortune of being captured. Our respects to the Adams ladies. Your excellencys very humble and very obedient servant</p>
        <div class="closer">
          <p class="signed">Cwf Dumas</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="docback">
        <div class="note-source" id="ADMS-06-16-02-0334-sn">
          
   <p style="text-indent: 1.5em; text-align: left;"><abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ recipients copy (A recipients copy is assumed to be in the hand of the signer unless it is otherwise described.) ]">RC</abbr> (<span class="ref-terms" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ &lt;expan&gt;Manuscripts and other materials, 16391889, in the Adams Manuscript Trust collection given to the Massachusetts Historical Society in 1956 and enlarged by a few additions of family papers since then. Citations in the present edition are simply by date of the original document if the original is in the main chronological series of the Papers and therefore readily found in the microfilm edition of the Adams Papers (see below).&lt;/expan&gt; ]">Adams Papers</span>); internal address: Auteuil  Son Excellence Mr. Adams.</p>

        </div>
        <div id="fn" class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#ADMS-06-16-02-0334-fn-0001-ptr" id="ADMS-06-16-02-0334-fn-0001">1</a>
          
   <p style="text-indent: 1.5em; text-align: left;">Dumas probably refers to Joseph IIs ultimately unsuccessful plan to obtain Bavaria in exchange for the Austrian Netherlands (<span class="ref-st" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ &lt;i&gt;The Cambridge Modern History,&lt;/i&gt; Cambridge, Eng., 19021911; repr. New York, 1969; 13 vols. ]"><span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Cambridge Modern Hist.,</span></span> 6:644, 646647).</p>

        </div>

        <div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#ADMS-06-16-02-0334-fn-0002-ptr" id="ADMS-06-16-02-0334-fn-0002">2</a>
          
   <p style="text-indent: 1.5em; text-align: left;">It is impossible to know specifically what Dumas enclosed for <abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ John Adams (17351826) ]">JA</abbr> to forward to America, but one possibility is his letter of this date to Pieter Johan van Berckel, the Dutch minister to the United States (<span class="ref-terms" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ &lt;expan&gt;Nationaal Archief, The Hague. For details on the Dumas Papers microfilm edition, see JA, &lt;i&gt;D&amp;amp;A,&lt;/i&gt; 3:910.&lt;/expan&gt; ]">Nationaal Archief</span>:Dumas Papers, Microfilm, Reel 2, f. 706). That letter is very similar to this one, particularly regarding the references to Joseph II and Bavaria and the concerns of Van Berckels wife about the Barbary pirates.</p>

        </div>

      </div>
